				<A href="edit.php?board=player&id=10908"><IMG alt="Edit/Delete Message" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/edit.gif" border=0></A> 
			    <A href="reply.php?board=player&id=10903"><IMG alt="Reply w/Quote" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/quote.gif" border=0></A>
			    <HR color=#000000 SIZE=-1>
			  	Investing in your planets will make your planets about as good as any other player (except Targoid, they're way better) that doesn't invest in their planets at all.  Unfortunately, that also means that if they invest, their production levels will outstrip you easily.  That's why they have Artifact Cooling Engine (but the Agerus have Missile Craters which is almost as good and their production is very good).  You will have to rely mainly on Commerce for your income.  You may even find it beneficial to stop investing in your planets after buildings stop being produced since your population will most likely be able to man any factories/laboratories/bases that you may be able to build (a friend and I tried a lot of different things).  The rest of us have to keep investing once we've started.<br />
<br />
Galactic University is the key and the way it works is described in the player's guide at http://avn.beheadedstraw.net/archspace2004_guide.html<br />
<br />
If I got the link wrong, embryodead will post the correct one later.<br />
<br />
If you build only laboratories on your Poor/ultra poor planets (reserve a few for military bases), then it will be easier to strip them of the labs once you are done researching without impacting your ability to make war.<br />
<br />
Good luck.<br />
<br />
I guess part of the balance is that Agerus have really poor Diplomacy (empire relations and such) and their commanders are only marginally better than Targoid commanders.			   <P align=right></P>
